sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1622001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Coupled Esterase and Terephthalic acid transporter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This BioBrick is the assembly of : - BBa_K808007, coding for the NB-Esterase 13. This Enzyme catalyzes the cutting of PET into terephthalic acid (TPA) and ethylene glycol. - BBa_K808030, coding for the Terephthalic acid transporter. This enzyme enables the entry of TPA into our bacteria.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Alma Chapet--Batlle, Lucas Krauss
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part is composed of 2 composite parts of the iGEM Registry of standard parts.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This BioBrick was meant to be a cluster in our Degradation.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K808030
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RBS-PhoA-His6tag-pNBEst13-Myctag-EstA is a long name for a long protein construct. It is a fusion protein which is secreted into the peri plasma in order to be integrated into the outer membran. When the phoA signal sequence is cut off, the N-terminus is formed by our pNB-Est13. This esterase shows actitivty towards PET and is anchored onto the cell by its inactive EstA membrane anchor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Marie Burghard, Henrik Cordes, Jascha Diemer, Sven Jager, Philipp Rottmann, Rene Sahm, Arne Wehling
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This is no natural or even native construct. We got it synthesized by GENEART. but added the RBS via PCR.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We got it synthesized by GENEART but added the RBS via PCR.
